rerun → read store → render widget → handle widget output → save state → render current UI

User changes a widget
    ---> Streamlit reruns the script from top to bottom
    ---> Normal Python variables are recreated
    ---> Widget state and st.session_state persist across reruns
    ---> The UI is rebuilt from the latest state

User changes something in UI
    ---> Streamlit reruns app.py from top to bottom. 
    ---> main() runs again
    ---> all UI render methods are called again. 
         widget values are remembered by Streamlit/session state
    ---> the widget that received input now returns a value/event
         whichever widget the user interacted with will now produce a changed return value.
    ---> that value travels back to main()
    ---> main() decides what to do
    ---> state is updated
    ---> UI is shown again from updated state


For example 
User types prompt and presses enter
    ---> Streamlit reruns app.py
    ---> main() runs again
    ---> sidebar renders again
    ---> uploader renders again
    ---> chat history renders again
    ---> chat input render() now returns the submitted prompt
    ---> main() receives that prompt
    ---> main() calls handle_user_prompt(...)
